cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Bonnie asks a good question. You have to decide whether 1NT is forcing by a passed hand. A lot of people play it is not forcing. In that case, here, East should pass 1NT with her flat 12 count. But here is 1 problem if you play it non-forcing. If passed responder has a 3-card limit raise, you may end up in 1NT instead of game in your major. There are 2 ways to solve that problem.|
PG| ***** 83 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|One is to play Drury, such that responder bids 2@C with a 3-card limit raise if partner is a 3rd or 4th seat opener. In which case the 1N bid will never be made with 3-card support.|
PG| ***** 84 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The other is to play it "semi-forcing" meaning it is sort of forcing, but opener is allowed to pass with a 5-3-3-2 12-14 count. That is what would have happened here, but as we saw, NT was just as good a contract as hearts anyway. Having said all that, unless I play Drury, I like to play 1NT as forcing even by a passed hand. I find it works out better for me.|
