qx||NT||at|
^BWest          ^lEast
^c@D× × × ×     ^m@DQ
^c@DQ           ^m@D× × × ×
^c@D× ×         ^m@DQ × ×
^c@D× × ×       ^m@DQ ×|
PG| ***** 167 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Note that you will fail to make four tricks if Diamonds are 4-1 with East having length. It is an important point this and needs careful consideration. If the Eastern opponent has @DQ 9 × × he can foil any plans you have by covering the @DJ with the @DQ. This way he will promote his @D9 into winning rank and hold you to three Diamond tricks.|
PG| ***** 168 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Now look at the alternative. Suppose you choose to play West for the @DQ. You cash the @DK first (you never know, the @DQ might appear on this trick, clearing your headache) and play a Diamond to the @D10. Now you will make four tricks whenever the Diamonds are divided in the following way:|
PG| ***** 169 ***** |


NT||at|
^bWest          ^lEast
^c@D× × × ×     ^m@DQ
^c@DQ           ^m@D× × × ×
^c@DQ ×         ^m@D× × ×
^c@DQ × ×       ^m@D× ×
^c@DQ × × ×     ^m@D×|
PG| ***** 170 ***** |


NT|^B@2
And you will make four tricks even if West has all five Diamonds (unlikely, given that he didn’t lead one).|
PG| ***** 171 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Since there are more layouts where you will be successful when West has the @DQ than when East has it you should play West for the Queen (and ignore partner’s pained expression when East does turn up with that card and the finesse fails. This is a percentage play, remember, not a sure thing).|
PG| ***** 172 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Put another way, you can cater for a 4-1 break when West has the four Diamonds but not if East has them. So the finesse through West is the percentage play, picking up four Diamond tricks just over 50% of the time.|
PG| ***** 173 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Playing the Diamonds the other way needs East to hold the @DQ and for Diamonds to break 3-2, reducing your chances to about 35%.|
